🔹 EX.NO.1 – Setup Cloud using OpenNebula (Detailed 8 Steps)
Start the system and open terminal, switch to root user using sudo -i.
Update the system packages using sudo apt update to ensure latest versions.
Upgrade installed packages using sudo apt upgrade.
Add OpenNebula repository and import its authentication key.
Install required OpenNebula packages (opennebula, sunstone, gate, flow).
Start and enable OpenNebula services in the system.
Verify installation by checking user and service status.
Open browser → type localhost:9869 and login using oneadmin credentials.
🔹 EX.NO.2 – Run Virtual Machines (Detailed 8 Steps)
Open the browser and navigate to OpenNebula dashboard (localhost:9869).
Login using administrator credentials (oneadmin).
Go to Instances section and select Virtual Machines (VMs).
Click on Create VM (+ icon) to start VM creation.
Enter VM details such as name, CPU count, RAM, and storage.
Select appropriate template or configuration for the VM.
Click on Create button to launch the VM instance.
Repeat the process to create multiple VMs and observe system capacity.
🔹 EX.NO.3 – VM Migration (Detailed 8 Steps)
Open OpenNebula dashboard in web browser.
Login with valid admin credentials.
Navigate to Infrastructure → Hosts/Clusters section.
Ensure multiple hosts are available or create new host.
Go to Instances → Virtual Machines.
Select the VM which needs to be migrated.
Click on Migrate option and choose destination host.
Confirm migration and verify successful movement of VM.
🔹 EX.NO.4 – Install C Compiler in VM (Detailed 8 Steps)
Open Virtual Machine Manager and create/start a VM.
Load operating system (e.g., Fedora/Ubuntu) in the VM.
Open terminal inside the VM (Ctrl + Alt + T).
Install GCC compiler using sudo apt-get install gcc.
Verify installation using gcc --version command.
Create a C program file using editor (vi filename.c).
Compile program using cc filename.c.
Execute compiled program using ./a.out and verify output.
🔹 EX.NO.5 – Google App Engine (Detailed 8 Steps)
Install Google Plugin for Eclipse IDE.
Open Eclipse and create a new web application project.
Generate sample project structure (Hello World application).
Review project directories like src, WEB-INF, and configuration files.
Configure appengine-web.xml file with application ID.
Run the application locally using Eclipse server.
Open browser and verify output at http://localhost:8888.
Deploy the application to Google App Engine cloud platform.
🔹 EX.NO.6 – CloudSim Simulation (Detailed 8 Steps)
Download CloudSim package and extract it into system.
Open Eclipse IDE and create a new Java project.
Import CloudSim libraries into the project classpath.
Initialize CloudSim using CloudSim.init() method.
Create data center with required characteristics.
Create broker and define virtual machines (VMs).
Create cloudlets (tasks) and assign them to VMs.
Run simulation and analyze output results such as execution time.
🔹 EX.NO.7 – Hadoop Installation (Detailed 8 Steps)
Install Java (JDK) and verify using java -version.
Install SSH and configure password-less SSH login.
Download Hadoop package and extract it.
Set environment variables in .bashrc file.
Configure Hadoop files (core-site.xml, hdfs-site.xml, etc.).
Format Namenode using Hadoop command.
Start Hadoop services (DFS and YARN).
Verify installation using web UI or Hadoop commands.
